f three of the largest\nmachine to??l companies here, the j\nAmerican Milling Machine Co.. the,\nI,od^*? Shipley Machine Tool Co.\nnnd the Cincinnati Milling Machine\nsay thev look for orders to be\ncoming in by March or April at a\nr.<te sufficient to keep them running\nf normal. The I^odge Shiplev j\nplant is still operating with a full\nforce on accumulated orders.\nTo Heneflt Industry.\n<?ne large tool concern believes\nthat payment of the Federal guarantee\nof earnings will immediately\nreact to the benefit of the industry.\n\"With this railway business out of;\nreckoning, the next best prospective\nbuyers are the automobile\nplant^. which ar* expected to be ir. j\nthe market by spring. Another com- 1\npuny. with an export business\nto nearly one-half its output, hasI\nxperienced heavy cancellations and\nr- quests to delay delivery until ex-\nchange improves*. Many of the cancellations\ncame from automobile\ncompanies in the United States.\nThere is the significant fact that\nuntil this year the automobile in- j\niustry wa.?* an expanding one?buy- I\ninsr new machinery, an dthe proba- i\nbility is that future orders are likely j\nto be mostly for replacement. Ma-\nchinery companies here are seeking!\nto develop business in new fields\nMachine tool companies report-in-\nouiries at an accelerated rate. Prac-\ntically none of the many concerns'\nhas reduced prices and several have j\nlarse stocks of high-priced steels.\nF.elief that lower prices are coming\nhas stopped foreign buying These I\nbuyers also t liberal credit.\nThe J. A Fay an^ Egan Company,\nmakers of woodworking machinery,\n/has >rders for many months ahead\nAnd Is running full time. The Lun kenheimer\nCompany, brass goods, is'\nrunning full time on engineering\nspecialties.\nThe heads of two cf the largest!\nFoup factories are very optimistic, j\n-One has not reduced forces and does\nnot expect to have to. The otic.r, j\nwhose 3.300 employes have been I\nworking four days a week, expects\n1 coon to restore a. six-day schedule, j\nKctailers* stocks are regarded as\nwell liquidated and orders are com- i\ning in. This may be due in part to\nextensive advertising, it was stated, i\nSmaller soap companies are running\nl-art time or are shut down.\nA can company with a national\nbusiness is rtmnlng with a full force,\nfull time and expects to keep pn j\nindefinitely. This is due to the j\nrefusal of its officers after October1\n1 to accept orders subject to cancellation.\nThe printing trade of the country\n4? reDorted slack bv\nthe Ault Wiborjc Co.. ink manu- j\nfacturers. but picking up is expect- 1\ned soon.\nThe Perk Ins-Campbell Co.. saddlery\nand harness, are receiving a\nnumber of reinstatements of orders\npreviously cancelled. Reinstate-\nments started coming in as soon\na* the company not'fled those who\nhad cancelled orders, as well as\nthose whose orders were still on!\nthe books, that\" prices had been\nreduced on many of the articles!\nmanufactured.\n<*tl?alate? Bvyftag.\nThis stimulated buying almost\nrv-r^where except in the South,\nthis house reports. The businses ih i\nleather belts is above normal and\npetting larger each day.\nCincinnati has eight large con-,\ncerns in harness, leather and tan-\nning. all of which report trading\nis quiet but apparently on the up- j\nturn.\nAlmost the entire shoe manufac-\nttirfo* industry, with its twenty\nfactories are running: slack and\ning women's shoes only. These\nfactories are sunning sla?*k and\n.?ome small ones are shut down.\nOne of the largest concerns reports j\nbuying for spring about 50 per cent;\nnormal. Since retailers' recent na-\nr.onal convention good orders which\ndealers had evidently delayed plac- I\nt jng until they talked with others j\nhave come in.\nThe foreign trade department of)\nthe Chamber of Commerce finds;\nthat many inqufries are coming j\nfrom Mexico, principally for ma- j\nchiaery and shoes. This city\nounts on getting a large slice\nof Mexican business because of\nttg command o