d\nof twenty years. 1900 to 1919, was\n2.5 per cent and the average underestimate\nfor the twenty years\n\\Vz per cent. In 1915 and 1916 it\nwas less than one-half of 1 per cent\n?and for the last three years It was\nabout 3 per cent under the final\ncensus report.\nThese later underestimates appear\nto have been due partly to the practice\nwhich developed during the war\nof prolonging the picking season\nand gathering unopened bolls after\nthe close of the picking season,\ncalled \"bollies\" and \"snaps,\" which\nwas encouraged by the relatively,\nhigh price for both lint and seed.\nThis new factor appears not to have\nbeen taken into account by thev?ot-|\nton reporters.\nRate Case Decision Due.\nDETROIT. Jan. 25.?Arguments in\nthe suit brought by seven railroads\nto present the State of Michigan\nfrom interfering with the collection\nof the passenger rate of 3 cents\na mile, recently authorized by the\nInterstate Commerce Commission,\nhave been completed and the case\ntaken upon consideration by the\nFederal Court. It is expected to\nhand down an opinion late in the\nmonth\nFORMER TAX Ch\nGOOD IN FIN\nJ\nf\nHH|^nBF\nWmm\nBEN L.\nice president and general manag\nj Corporation, w hose pleasing persi\ngood in the business world just a\nlife when lie acted as tax collector\nPrince came to Washington i\nj sentative Rufus Hardy as his pri\nhe was clerk of the committee on\nis married and is the father of a 6member\nof the Board of Trade, tl\nMasonic order.\nCOTTON NERVOUS I\nAS PRICE DROPS!\nJanuary Breaks 100 Points,\nBut Partly Recovers When\nContracts Mature.\nNEW YORK, Jan Generally j\nthe cotton market today was n??r-,\nvous and irreprular as a result of bus j\ni flw?tuatk>n?* in .January, ?Mtd th? j'\neloge was weaker\nThe market op?*n#?<l easier at a de-\ncllne of 12 to 30 points The fea-\nture in the market was the final'\nevening up of January contracts'\nwhich matured at noon\nLate in the morning there was\nv.ome January for sale, and within al\nj few minutes 