buyers are off the\nmarket. A little flour is moving to\nManila.\nThe west coast of South America\nis inquiring and payment of bills\nis more prompt, but buyers are not\nkeeping to tijeir contracts to make\npayment in American money. North\ncoast millers exported a shipload of\nflour to Brazil early in the winter\nand on arrival it was rejected,\n^fillers say they cannot afford to\nbuild up a foreign trade and involve\ncapital in a line of business\nof this character and prefer to wait\nfurther contracts until exchange is\nnearer par.\nCHICAGO LIVESTOCK.\nCHICAGO. Jan. 25.?Hogs?Lights\nactive. 15c to 25c higher; others\nslow, 10c to 15c higher than yesterday's\naverage: big packers doing\nlittle; average cost Monday. S9.25,\nweignt Z6\\*.\nCattle?Beef steers active, mostly\nir?c to 25c higher; early 1op, $10.50;\n11 head prime Angus held higher;\nshe stock and calves steady to\nstrong; bulls steady; stock and\nfeeding steers, 15c to 25c higher.\nSheep Killing classes about\nsteady; lamb. top. $11.25: top yearlings.\n$9.35; top ewes, early $5.75;\nprime 115-lb wethers. $6.35; few\nsales feeder lambs up to $9.75; look\nsteady.\nAllan E.Walker^Cq\nASSURED\nincome\n:;i;q? M H\nFIRST\nMORTGAGES\nigh ON\n.nd WASHINGTON\nJ REAL i-.\nars. s^^TATE.,^-'\nIER CO., INC.\nitaaranre Brokem\nSouthern Building\nAMERICANS WIL1\nIN CANAD\nBoom Not Looked fo\nFor Dominion's\nF\nf8p?ciai to Busimest Section of Th? Wuh?\ninfton Herald.)\nOttawa. Jan. 25.? Prospect* for\nbusings* in Canada during 1921. A\nwide survey of best opinion leads\nto the conclusion that they arc\ngood. A boom I* not looked foe.\nbut a strong demand for goods is\nexpected. Of this American exporters\nwill get a large share unless\nd tariff war starts between the two\nCountries.\nThe following statements from\nCanada's leading industrial factors\ngive a true line on the Canadian\nbusiness outlook:\nA. Whyte. vice president. Canadian\nCar and Foundry Company.\nLtd., Montreal:\n\"We think there Is no reason why\n1921 should not be prosperous. The\nprospect of increased immigration\nis particularly bright, and this\n?hould result in increased production\nin those commodities which\nCanada can profitably export in\ncompetition with other countries.\nLabor conditions should be more\nsatisfactory than in 1920. and a decrease\nin the price of raw materials\nshould place a lot of business\nwhich is being held up at present.\nSo far as the iron and steel trades\nare concerned the future is encouraging,\nIn view of the admitted\nshortage of equipment of all kinds i\non the Canadian railways.\"\nW. J McKay. Dominion Iron ami\nSteel Company. Ltd. Montreal'\nThe steel situation to us looks\nbetter and brighter than any of th?oth\nr trades, and it is just a matter\nof sitting tight for another month\nK. R. Bartleit. Chase Tractor*.\n'orporation, Ltd Toronto:\n\"The outlook for 1*21 is remark i\nbl v good and tractor manufaciurers\nwill base production on orders\nfor spring deliveries. Everything\npoints to a record spring\nbusiness.\"\nWilliam M Cray, vie? president\nCray-Dort Motors. Ltd. Chatham.\n'ntario:\nThe outlook for the 1$21 mark? i\nis very favorable. l?ur sales connections\nthroughout the country report\nexcellent prospects. We have\nconfidence there wil! b** a brisk revival\nof industrial activity within a\nfew months\nGeorge Chanhoon. jr.. pr -sident.\nLaurentide Company. Ltd. Grandmere.\nProvince Quebec:\n\"The outlook for 11*21 is good.\nAll of the newsprint mills are contracted\nup to lull capacity and th\nhave the assurance of the publishers\nthat they expect to use the full\namount of their contracts.\"\nR. G. Tolmie, Canadian Cottons.\nLtd.. Montreal.\n\"With a return to normal prices,\nwe are confident of a healthy revival\nin business conditions in 1*21.\nThe world's shelves are really bare\nof goods Manufacturers cannot afford\nto take chances and are cur\nlulling proauction 01 anything but\ngoods actually sold. Meanwhile,\nconsumption by the general public\ngoes merrily on. and. although undoubtedly\nrestricted by a certain\namount of unemployment, this consumption\nhas been exceeding production\nThe ultimate outcome is\nobvious.\"\nW. Tinker. Canadian Woolens.\nLtd Peterboro. Ont.:\nThe year 1921 should h? a splendid\nyear for the cloth and yarn\ntrade. One of the largest crops\nwhich the Dominion has ev-r seen\nhas just been marketed. The money\nto purchase goods is n the country.\nand although prices will be\nlower in the future, business should\nimprove very materially by spring\nThomas Hell. The Bell Furnitur**\nCompany. Ltd. Southampton:\n\"Thf> furniture factories in Canada\nhave increased their production\nduring the last eighteen months\nand are able to supply the Canadian\nmarket We believe, considering\ncrop conditions, we ai? bound ?o\nha\\> a better year in 1?21 than in\n1920.\"\nE. C. Scythes. Nordheimcr Piano\nand Music Company. Ltd.. Toronto:\n\"There is wealth in the hands nl\nthe masses. People may be holding\nback on buying, but that is a gen\nOf I\nSec\nAN Agency Acco\nk deuil and plac\nand handling such\nof dividends, crediti\nthe faithful and acc\nThis is a convenient\nous details involved\nover them. The sa\nAccount is well wor\n\nSecurit\n15\n7th\n436 Seventh Street, S.^\n-SHARE\n'A'S PROSPERITY\nr, but Strong Demand\nloods is Expected.\neral condition, and it in one that]\nthe salesman lias a chance of over- I\ncoming.\nSir Frederick Williams-Taylor. I\ngeneral manager. Bank of Montreal:)\n\"We are looking forward to the I\nyear 1921 with considerable confi-\ndence. based on the known financial\ncondition of the country at large,\nand especially the buying power of\nthe agricultural communities, because\nof the abundant crops of\n1920.\"\nC. E. Kdmondf, Christie Brown\nCo.. Ltd.. Toronto. Canada's biggest\nbiscuit firm:\n\"Our outlook for 1921 is optimistic.\nImmigration is bound to increase. 1\nNeglected public works will be un- j\ndertaken and more land placed un- j\nder cultivation.\"\nA. E. Hampson